Public health, economics, and data interpretation have all faced di6iculties as a result of the global covid-19 pandemic. To learn more about the virus's distribution, patterns of fatalities, and rates of recovery, governments, researchers, and the general public have resorted to data analytics. In order to find patterns and connections in the kaggle coronavirus report dataset, this project uses exploratory data analysis, regression modeling, classification, and clustering approaches. Finding insights that could help data analysts and public health decision-makers understand pandemic dynamics is the main goal.
The original dataset included daily records of covid-19 cases at the country level. I removed the province/state column because of redundancy and a high number of missing values and then converted the date field to datetime format. Missing values were filled with zeroes based on the lack of data indicated no reported cases for the category. A new column, active, was created to measure ongoing infections as the di6erence between confirmed cases and the total of recoveries and deaths.
